properties.name: Country Music Hall of Fame Museum
properties.description: Posted by Andrew2 222 Fifth Avenue South Nashville, Tennessee Before 1963 the plaques given to Country Music Hall of Fame inductees were kept in the Tennessee State Museum. But in 1963 the Country Music Association announced it\'s plans to build a Country Music Hall of Fame Museum on Music Rowe in Nashville. That same year the state of Tennessee chartered the Country Music Foundation. The CMF was a non-profit, educational organization that was charged with operating the museum. The original museum opened on April 1, 1967 and closed on December 31, 2000. The new 37 million dollar museum (seen above) opened on May 17, 2001. Jimmie Rogers, Hank Williams, and Fred Rose are just of the few who are in the Hall of Fame Museum.

properties.name: Doak Campbell Stadium
properties.description: Posted by Andrew2Florida State University, Tallahassee, FLDoak Campbell Stadium has risen alongside the Florida State football program. Since the stadium\'s opening on October 7, 1950 thousands of fans pack the stadium for every home game to see the finest college football action.The stadium is named after Doak S. Campbell, a past president of FSU. The stadium sits across from the Moore Athletic Center on Pensacola St. and Stadium Drive. The stadium also has a Prescription Athletic Turf, which was installed in 1988. It quickly rids itself from any drainage problems with a system of underground pumps. The stadium has just recently added a huge television screen named the War Board. One thing that has and never will change is Florida State\'s winning record at home! I have visited this stadium once to see FSU tear USC apart! Doak Campbell Stadium is a very enjoyable place to visit.

properties.name: Eiffel Tower
properties.description: Posted by Andrew2Gustave Eiffel Ave. Paris, France 75007The Eiffel Tower was designed by French engineer Alexandre Gustave Eiffel for the Paris Exposition of 1889. The tower is 984 ft. tall and consits of an open iron framework making it currently the highest manmade structure in the world. It was the largest attraction at the exposition and today it remains the most recognized structure in all Europe. But it was nearly never built. After being awarded the contract to build the tower, Eiffel realized the Exposition Comittee would only grant one fourth of the money needed to construct the tower. Eiffel himself didn\'t have the finances to build the tower. He made a deal that would make him a very rich man. He agreed to independentley find the funders for the tower but he would get sole control of the tower and it\'s profits for twenty years. To everyones suprise (including Eiffel\'s) the tower was paid off in it\'s first year.

Every Sunday morning 300 plus people come to hear senior pastor Mark Creech\'s message. The rest of the church staff consits of Minister of Education Randy Willett, Interim Music pastor Brent Lipham, Youth pastor Ryan Rouse, and also our Spanish pastor Jorge Gonzalez. Our Service times our Sunday School at 9:30,Morning Worship at 10:30,and Evening Worship at 6:00. Also on Wedensday we have Mission Friends, RA\'s, G.A.\'s, Youth, College, and Discipleship classes at 6:30. Also we have prayer meeting. Also on Monday nights we have a youth sports night.

properties.name: Louisiana Superdome
properties.description: Posted by Andrew2Sugar Bowl Drive, New Orleans, LA 70112Home to the NFL\'s New Orleans Saints football teame This dome was constructed in 1967 by the architectural firm of Curtis and Davis. The Superdome is the largest fixed dome structure in the world standing at 273 ft. tall and has a diameter of 680 ft. And I can say from personal experience you can\'t appreciate the size of this structure until you see it in person. Also, in 2005 the Superdome recieved national attention when it housed thousands of evacuees seeking shelter from Hurricane Katrina. When I went to New Orleans recently to work on a mission project. I heard many stories of how terrible the conditions were in the Superdome, and the things that went on in their were so bad some men couldn\'t even bring themselves to talk about it.

properties.name: Statue of Liberty
properties.description: Posted by Andrew2Liberty Island New York, NYThis large beuatiful statue was presented to the United States from France in 1886. It stands at Liberty Island as a welcome to all visitors, immigrants, and returning Americans. The copper patina-clad statue was dedicated on October 28, 1886. It commerates the centennial of the United States and is a gesture of friendship from France to America. It was sculpted by Fredric Auguste Bartholdi. Alexandre Gustave Eiffel designed the internal structure. Eugene Viollet-le-Due was responsible for the choice of copper in the statue\'s construction. The torch is coated in goald leaf. The statue stands at 305 ft tall.

properties.name: Sydney Opera House
properties.description: Posted by Andrew2Bennelong Point, Sydney 2000This opera house was designed by Jorn Utzon, a Danish architect. The Sydney Opera House is one of the world\'s most distinctive 20th century builings, and one of the most famous performing arts venues in the world. As well as featuring theatre, ballet, and musical productions, the Opera House is home to Opera Austrailia, the Sydney Theatre Company, and the Sydney Symphony. The Opera House is 605 feet long, 388 feet wide. It is supportedon 580 concrete piers sunk up to 25 meters below sea level. Its power supply is equivilant for a town of 25,000 people. The power is distributed by 645 kilometers of electrical cable.

properties.name: Taj Mahal
properties.description: Posted by Andrew2Agra, Uttar PradeshThis wonder of the world is located in Agra, India. It was built by Emperor Shan Jahan in memory of his favorite wife Mumtaz Mahal.It is most famous for it\'s white domed marble. The Taj Mahal is also considered to be the finest example of Mughal architecture. Mughal architecture is a combination of elements from Persian,Turkish,Indian,and Islamic architectural stlyes. In 1983, the Taj Mahal became a World Heritage Site.It was also cited as the jewel of Muslim art in India and one of the most admired masterpieces of the world\'s heritage. The Taj Mahal was believed to be completed around 1648 It is also believed to be designed by Ustad Ahmad Lahauri. I have to say I have not visited this beautiful place, but I sure would like to.

properties.name: The Leaning Tower of Pisa
properties.description: Posted by Andrew2Piazza dei Miracoli, PisaThis tower is the bell tower for the Cathedral in Pisa, Italy. It\'s construction began in August of 1173 and continued for about 200 years. The architect for this project is still unknown. The tower was originally designed to be vertical. Unfortunatley, the tower started to incline during construction. Both because of it\'s inclination and it\'s beauty from it\'s construction to today it has recieved special attention. During it\'s construction efforts were made to hault the inclination through the use of special construction devices but they all failed. Today interventions are being made with the sub-soil to significantly reduce the inclination of the tower to insure iy will have a long life.

properties.name: The Varsity
properties.description: Posted by Andrew261 North Ave. Atlanta, GA 30308The orignal Varsity was opened in 1928 on a 70 by 120 lot with a white picket fence by a man named Frank Gordy. Frank Gordy was a man with 2,000 dollars and million dollar taste buds. Through his deication to freshness, superior quality, advanced technology, and serving the best fast food he gained a reputation that is known worldwide. The Varsity has hosted well known people from the entertainment industry, sports industry, the Governor\'s mansion, the White House, and as well as from around the globe. The Varsity has six different locations including the one in Atlanta, Georgia. On average the Varsity produces two miles of hot dogs, a ton of onions, 2,500 pounds of potatoes, 5,000 fried pies, and 300 gallons of chili from scratch. I\'ve frequently visited the Varsity in Atlanta, Georgia and I\'d have to say it is a great experience.
